INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '49f46f3d-c7ec-4eee-a547-eb313f5a1042',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Gin Middleware — Pipeline Order, Global vs Route-Specific$escape$,
  $escape$Gin middleware is just a `HandlerFunc` that calls `c.Next()` to pass control down the chain — or `c.Abort()` to short-circuit it. The order you register middleware is the order it executes, both before and after `c.Next()`. Global middleware registered via `r.Use()` runs on every request. Route-specific middleware is scoped by attaching it directly to a route group or individual route.

A common mistake: registering a logger after an auth middleware means unauthenticated requests never get logged. Register your logger first. Similarly, `gin.Recovery()` should always be the outermost middleware so it catches panics from everything downstream, including other middleware.

Group-scoped middleware is powerful for applying auth only to protected routes without polluting public ones. The middleware stack for a request is the engine-level stack plus the group stack plus the route-level handlers — all merged into a single `HandlersChain` slice. Gin executes them sequentially via index, so code after `c.Next()` in an outer middleware runs after all inner handlers complete — giving you natural pre/post hooks.$escape$,
  $escape$r := gin.New()
r.Use(gin.Logger())      // 1st: logs all requests
r.Use(gin.Recovery())    // 2nd: catches panics in all subsequent handlers

// Public routes — no auth
r.GET("/health", healthHandler)

// Protected group — auth middleware scoped here only
api := r.Group("/api", AuthMiddleware())
{
    api.GET("/profile", profileHandler)
    api.POST("/bytes", rateLimiter(), createByteHandler) // route-level middleware
}$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
